Sure. But this doesn't make the Yen a safe haven. It's a funding currency behaving like a safe haven. Initial wave of risk liquidation goes to Yen, but then the correlation should break down on rotation from Yen to real safe haven assets. So eventually USDJPY up even in risk off.

US equities had nearly a decade of immunity to bad news on account of central bank policy that incentivized excessive risk taking, in an effort to artificially prop global sentiment. It's fair to assume the reversal of this policy is triggering the opposite reaction.

FX traders have been having a hard time calling for US Dollar upside despite flight to safety, given US protectionism. But if the Yen, which isn't even a safe haven, can rally in risk off, I think it's fair to assume the Dollar, which is a safe haven, should be able to find bids.

One of the best ways to identify an early stage of a bear market is to watch how the market behaves into rallies. The way a trend will go from well supported on dips, to all of a sudden, well capped into rallies, is one of those things that really drives home the change going on.
